{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12658"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12658"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.03,0.09,0.11,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35185"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5131"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"882"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35185"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA neonate was born to a 41-year-old mother at 38 weeks of gestation with a birth weight of 2.9 kg. The neonate has normal vitals. Systemic examinations are also normal, except for the findings shown in the photograph (image) on the abdominal examination. Externally, no other birth anomalies are visible.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following chromosomal abnormalities should this neonate be screened for?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trisomies 13, 18, and 21","Monosomies","Sex chromosome aneuploidies","Genetic mosaicism","Single gene defects"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn anterior midline abdominal mass at the site of the umbilical cord insertion covered by a membrane, as shown in the image, is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eomphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E. Advanced maternal age, as in this case, is one of the important risk factors for omphalocele in newborns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOmphalocele can be isolated but is more frequently associated with other congenital anomalies and syndromes such as Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome and \u003Cstrong\u003Etrisomies 13, 18, and 21.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle gene defects \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E mosaicism \u003C/strong\u003Eare not commonly associated with omphalocele. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESex chromosome aneuploidies \u003C/strong\u003Elike Turner syndrome may have omphaloceles associated, but they are less common than those with \u003Cstrong\u003Etrisomies.\u003C/strong\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonosomies\u003C/strong\u003E are remarkably rare in humans and practically limited to chromosomes 21 or X.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysiologic midgut herniation occurs around the \u003Cstrong\u003Esixth week\u003C/strong\u003E of development when the abdominal contents become too large to be contained in the abdominal cavity and protrude at the base of the umbilical cord. This can easily be identified on prenatal ultrasound between the 9th and 11th weeks of gestation. The hernia reduces at \u003Cstrong\u003E12 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E of gestation, and when it persists, it is no longer physiological. \u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalocele \u003C/strong\u003Eoccurs when the gut contents fail to rotate and return to the abdominal cavity. The liver is never present in the physiologic midgut herniation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIsolated omphalocele in a macrosomic baby with clinical presentation of hypoglycemia suggests a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003EBeckwith-Wiedemann syndrome.\u003C/strong\u003E Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome, a genetic imprinting disorder, is the most common overgrowth syndrome that can present as a wide and varied clinical spectrum with a predisposition to developing tumors during early childhood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Omphalocele can be isolated but is more frequently associated with other congenital anomalies and syndromes such as Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome and trisomies 13, 18, and 21.","The physiologic midgut hernia reduces at 12 weeks of gestation, and when it persists, it is no longer physiological."],"references":["Chen CP. Syndromes and disorders associated with omphalocele (III): single gene disorders, neural tube defects, diaphragmatic defects and others. Taiwan J Obstet Gynecol. 2007 Jun;46(2):111-20. doi: 10.1016/S1028-4559(07)60004-7. PMID: 17638618.","Conner P, Vejde JH, Burgos CM. Accuracy and impact of prenatal diagnosis in infants with omphalocele. Pediatr Surg Int. 2018 Jun;34(6):629-633.","Zahouani T, Mendez MD. Omphalocele. [Updated 2023 Jan 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519010/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12658"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19798"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19798"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25dc8a9e-2ab2-438d-ab2b-8c6083fc42b4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25dc8a